{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-ad63ba661d6f5846","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629194607","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\n\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\n\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\n\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\n\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\n\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\n\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\n\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\n\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\n\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\n\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\n\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\n\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\n\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\n\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\n\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\n\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\n\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\n\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\n\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\n\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\n\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\n\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\n\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\n\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\n\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\n\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\n\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\n\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\n\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\n\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\nBytes: 6110\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\n\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\nBytes: 7153\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":870013,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-ad63ba661d6f5846","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629194607","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\n\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\n\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\n\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\n\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\n\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\n\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\n\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\n\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\n\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\n\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\n\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\n\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\n\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\n\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\n\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\n\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\n\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\n\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\n\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\n\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\n\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\n\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\n\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\n\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\n\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\n\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\n\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\n\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\n\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\n\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\nBytes: 6110\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\n\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\nBytes: 7153\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":870013,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782766097562}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-ad63ba661d6f5846","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629194607","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\n\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\n\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\n\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\n\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\n\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\n\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\n\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\n\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\n\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\n\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\n\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\n\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\n\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\n\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\n\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\n\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\n\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\n\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\n\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\n\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\n\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\n\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\n\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\n\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\n\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\n\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\n\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\n\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\n\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\n\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\nBytes: 6110\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\n\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\nBytes: 7153\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":870013,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782766097562}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to follow steps:\n\n1. Call mcp with tool \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", args \"{}\". Use mcp function.\n\nWe must repeat as described: if returns state waiting, call again with after_version. Otherwise if ready, we then have prompt, turn, limits, etc. Then we need to fetch case details, evidence etc, decide vote, then submit via mcp.\n\nWe must not include other keys in mcp call besides tool and args.\n\nLet's call.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-ad63ba661d6f5846","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b","usage":{"input":2009,"output":136,"cacheRead":32,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2177,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782766088140,"responseId":"gen-1782766088-bn5h6RToNPeqDYZWqAhF"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-ad63ba661d6f5846","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629194607\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 870013\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629194607\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\\n\\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\\n\\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\\n\\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\\n\\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\\n\\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\\n\\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\\n\\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\\n\\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\\n\\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\\n\\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\\n\\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\\n\\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\\n\\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\\n\\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\\n\\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\\n\\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\\n\\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\\n\\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\\n\\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\\n\\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\\n\\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\\n\\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\\n\\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\\n\\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\\n\\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\\n\\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\\nSource: Rev\\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\\n\\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\\n\\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\\n\\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\\n\\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\\n\\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \\\"That man can play.\\\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\\n\\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\\n\\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\\n\\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\\n\\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \\\"ronaldo\\\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\\n\\nRelevant page text:\\n\\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\n\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\n\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\n\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\n\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\n\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\n\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\n\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\n\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\n\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\n\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\n\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\n\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\n\\n2026 World Cup\\n\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\n\\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\\nBytes: 6110\\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\\nBytes: 7153\\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":870013,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629194607","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is not simplistic. The decisive issue is not whether the word mechanics are satisfied. It is whether this market’s phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” read with Kalshi’s mention-market terms, includes Trump’s public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program, or instead silently narrows the market to only the formal on-stage draw transcript.\n\nThe record already gives the council the core materials. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the market title, the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, the strike “Ronaldo,” Kalshi’s challenged No resolution, and the requested Yes resolution. The reporter-exchange transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, places President Trump at the John F. Kennedy Center on December 5, 2025, in remarks expressly tied to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw. In that exchange he discusses the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, soccer, and the draw setting. In the material passage he refers to Ronaldo by name more than once, including saying that he met Ronaldo, that Ronaldo was fantastic, and that Ronaldo is a great player. If that exchange falls within the market’s event period, the strike resolves Yes.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, support that reading. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the relevant time period, allow time periods to be event- or context-based, and require the word to appear as a distinct standalone unit. “Ronaldo” satisfies the standalone-word rule. The terms do not say that an event-based market automatically excludes public remarks at the venue, with the FIFA president present, on the very subject of the draw, merely because they occur before the formal stage presentation begins. The terms do exclude things like behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. That exclusion matters because it shows what Kalshi knew how to exclude. The packet transcript is not presented as a rehearsal or sound check; it is public reporter questioning tied to the draw.\n\nThe defense will likely rely on ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, which flags a separate archive page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw and says the local session did not retrieve the full formal transcript. That evidence is useful because it frames the real dispute. It does not prove the formal program contained “Ronaldo,” and plaintiff does not need to prove that if the market boundary reasonably includes the event-linked reporter exchange. Nor does it prove that Kalshi told traders the formal program was the only source.\n\nThere are provenance points the council should weigh carefully. The reporter-exchange transcript includes a source URL and a note that the Office of Communications released the transcript on December 8, 2025 and corrected it on January 2, 2026; it also says some portions could not be verified because audio was incomplete. That caveat should not be ignored. But the Ronaldo passage itself is transcribed, not bracketed as inaudible, and the transcript’s setting, date, and subject matter all tie it to the World Cup Draw event.\n\nSo the burden question is this: more likely than not, did the market wording and terms clearly exclude the public pre-program draw-venue exchange? If the answer is no, the challenged No resolution cannot stand. The market asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw, and the case-packet transcript shows that in the event’s public setting, on the event’s subject, Trump said “Ronaldo.” Plaintiff will ask the council to resolve the strike Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with a narrow concession and a broader burden point. The packet transcript for the pre-event reporter exchange, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” If this were simply a question whether those letters appear in that transcript, plaintiff would have an easy case. But the proposition is not that broad. It asks whether the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” should resolve Yes because a public reporter exchange at the venue immediately before the formal program was inside the market’s covered period.\n\nThat is the missing link plaintiff must prove by a preponderance. The market-page packet, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the title, strike, contract family, challenged No resolution, and requested Yes resolution. It does not itself define the event boundary or say that all same-day, same-venue, event-adjacent remarks before the draw counted. The words “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” naturally point to the draw event, not every press interaction around it.\n\nThe reporter-exchange file is plaintiff’s strongest record item, but it also carries the defense’s strongest boundary signal. Its own title is “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” It says the President’s remarks were joined in progress; it contains repeated inaudible sections; and its note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. Those caveats do not erase the Ronaldo passage, but they matter for weight and source discipline. More importantly, the source describes a reporter exchange prior to the draw, not the formal draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not collapse that distinction. They define the underlying as words used by the covered entity during the specified time period, and they allow event-based time periods. They also recognize that, when the time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included, and they separately address live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, official presentations, behind-the-scenes material, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That structure matters because it treats event scope as a real condition, not a formality. A public transcript being official or topical is not the same as proof that it was officially broadcast, published, or designated as part of the market’s event time period.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, reinforces why the council should not shortcut the issue. It identifies a separate archived transcript page for Trump’s formal attendance remarks at the draw, while candidly saying this packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript and therefore does not prove whether that transcript contains “Ronaldo.” The defense will not overclaim from that gap. But plaintiff also cannot fill it by treating a prior reporter exchange as equivalent to the formal program.\n\nThe decisive proof in later phases should be the market-specific rule/source page, the full formal draw transcript or recording, and any official source showing whether the pre-program reporter exchange was actually included in the market’s covered event period. On this opening record, plaintiff has shown a word in a prior reporter exchange. It has not yet shown that the market required Kalshi to count that exchange as words said during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The defense will ask the council to uphold the No resolution unless that missing boundary proof is supplied.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits record now answers the defense’s boundary objection by a preponderance.\n\nStart with what is no longer seriously disputed. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies this as the Kalshi market “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, in the PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION family, with “Ronaldo” as the strike, a challenged No resolution, and a requested Yes resolution. The defense concedes the reporter-exchange packet, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, contains the standalone word “Ronaldo.” The generic terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, require the word to appear as a distinct unit; “Ronaldo” plainly does.\n\nThe live issue is whether these remarks count as part of the covered event. They should. The case-packet transcript and the newly submitted American Presidency Project extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, are not stray gossip or backstage fragments. They show a public exchange at the Kennedy Center, with President Trump and FIFA President Infantino, repeatedly organized under World Cup and World Cup Draw headings. The relevant page includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” The questions and answers are about the draw, the World Cup, FIFA, host cities, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. In that same event-linked exchange, Trump says he met Ronaldo, says Ronaldo came to the White House, says Ronaldo is great, and later compares himself to Ronaldo and Messi.\n\nThe defense’s strongest phrase is “Prior to” in the transcript title. But “prior to the formal program” is not the same thing as “outside the FIFA World Cup Draw market event.” Kalshi did not title the market “What will Trump say on the formal stage transcript only?” It asked what Trump would say during the FIFA World Cup Draw. The record shows Trump speaking publicly at the draw venue, immediately before the formal program, on the draw’s subject matter, with the head of FIFA participating. Under ordinary event usage, the public press/red-carpet component at the venue can be part of the event, especially when the market text gives no narrower cutoff.\n\nThe terms reinforce that the Exchange knows how to draw exclusions. They exclude behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. This was not a rehearsal, sound check, or private backstage recording. It was an official public transcript of a reporter exchange about the World Cup Draw. The terms also allow event/context-based time periods and do not impose a default rule that only the formal stage segment counts.\n\nProvenance cuts in plaintiff’s favor, with a candid limitation. The packet transcript says the remarks were at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, released by the Office of Communications and later corrected; the APP extract preserves the source page and material text. The note that some audio was incomplete affects bracketed inaudibles, but the Ronaldo passages are transcribed words, repeated in ordinary text, and corroborated by the primary page extract.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, does not defeat the claim. It proves a separate formal transcript exists and was not retrieved in the packet. It does not prove Kalshi limited this market to that formal transcript, does not prove the pre-program exchange was excluded, and does not erase the broader event language that traders actually saw.\n\nOn this record, Kalshi’s No resolution depends on an unstated narrowing rule. The more natural and fair reading is that public, event-linked remarks at the draw venue immediately before the formal program were within the World Cup Draw event context. Because Trump said “Ronaldo” there, the strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has proved only half the case. The record shows that Trump said the standalone word “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. The defense does not contest the word mechanics. The unresolved element is whether plaintiff has shown, by a preponderance, that this prior reporter exchange was within the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThe best evidence on that boundary points against plaintiff. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives only the public title, family, strike, and challenged resolution. It does not say that pre-program press availability, red-carpet exchanges, or every same-venue public remark counted. Plaintiff’s APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, improves the provenance of the reporter exchange, but its own title remains “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 [FIFA] World Cup Draw.” That is not a defense gloss; it is the source’s description of the event relationship. The page’s topical headings show subject matter. They do not transform a prior reporter exchange into the draw itself.\n\nThe governing terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, also make event scope a real condition. They define the underlying as words used by the entity during the specified time period. For event-based periods, the Exchange may specify what is included; the rules separately address official presentations, live streams, broadcasts, official recordings, behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings. That framework would be unnecessary if any public, official, event-adjacent remark automatically counted. The terms support counting words during the event, and content presented as part of the official event; they do not supply a default rule that remarks “prior to” the draw count because they occurred at the same venue and concerned the same subject.\n\nDefendant’s submitted formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, confirms why the distinction matters. Rev’s readable transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing” and covers the formal peace-prize and draw-assistant program: Trump’s award remarks, his formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and his participation in drawing the United States. In that formal-program extract, the word “Ronaldo” does not appear. That is not offered as the sole official source of market resolution; it is offered to show that there is a distinct formal program, and that the admitted Ronaldo language comes from a different source category: the reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s theory relies on a chain of inferences: public plus official plus at the Kennedy Center plus about the World Cup plus immediately before the program equals “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” Each link has some weight, but the chain still lacks the decisive market-specific link. No admitted Kalshi rule page says the market included pre-program reporter exchanges. No admitted official broadcast page shows that this exchange was part of the formal presentation. No admitted source says the market time period opened at the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability rather than at the formal drawing program.\n\nProvenance also counsels caution. The reporter transcript was joined in progress, contains repeated inaudible portions, and notes that some remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. The Ronaldo passage itself is readable, so this does not defeat word occurrence. It does, however, underscore that plaintiff is asking the council to stretch a corrected, partial, prior-to-event reporter transcript across the market boundary without the market-specific source evidence that would justify the stretch.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note, ev_eac0f81b7818_formal-draw-archive-note, candidly says the packet did not retrieve the full formal transcript. Defendant has now supplied a readable formal-program comparator. The resulting record shows two different things: Trump did say “Ronaldo” in an APP reporter exchange before the draw, and the formal draw program evidence now in the record does not contain that strike. Under the preponderance standard, plaintiff needed more than event adjacency to overturn Kalshi’s No resolution. It needed proof that the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period included that prior exchange. It has not supplied that proof. The council should reject the proposition and uphold No.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new Rev exhibit narrows the dispute but does not resolve it.\n\nPlaintiff accepts what ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111 can fairly prove: the preserved Rev formal-program extract is a distinct transcript, and its text does not contain “Ronaldo.” But that is not the market rule. It is not the source hierarchy. It is not evidence that Kalshi told traders “only this formal transcript counts.” It is simply a comparator showing that the formal stage program and the pre-program reporter exchange were different source artifacts.\n\nDefendant’s own comparator also weakens its hard boundary. The Rev transcript is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” yet it begins with peace-prize and certificate remarks, includes Trump’s award remarks, and only later has Infantino say that they are “now going to do the draw.” In other words, even defendant’s formal-program evidence treats the “World Cup Drawing” event as broader than the literal draw mechanics. Once that is true, the question is not whether every second before the ball draw is excluded. The question is where the market reasonably drew the event boundary.\n\nOn that question, plaintiff’s evidence remains stronger. The APP transcript extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, and the packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, show public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, organized under World Cup Draw Event headings, about the draw, ticket sales, teams, host countries, the audience, and the event setting. That is not a rehearsal, sound check, backstage exchange, or unofficial recording. Those are the categories ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms excludes. This exchange does not fit them.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a market-specific sentence expressly including pre-program press remarks. But under a preponderance standard, the absence that matters is the opposite: there is no admitted market-specific sentence excluding them. The market title in ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not what he would say “in the formal Rev transcript” or “after Infantino says the draw begins.” If Kalshi meant that narrower rule, it needed to make that limitation clear before resolving No.\n\nThe record therefore shows two compatible facts: Ronaldo is absent from a formal-program comparator, and Ronaldo is present in an official public transcript from the draw venue immediately before that program, in remarks repeatedly tied to the World Cup Draw event. The second fact is enough unless the first comes with an exclusionary rule. It does not. Plaintiff’s Yes resolution remains the better reading of the market and terms.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. Defendant does not argue that only the mechanical drawing of balls counts. A formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program can include ceremony, remarks, awards, and draw mechanics. The relevant line is not “literal draw mechanics only.” It is the line between the official event program or presentation and a separate reporter exchange whose own source describes it as “Prior to” the World Cup Draw.\n\nThat distinction is exactly what the record now shows. Defendant’s Rev exhibit, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is a formal-program comparator. It includes the peace-prize segment, Trump’s award remarks, Infantino’s introduction of Trump as a draw assistant, Trump’s formal answer about the World Cup in the United States, and the draw action itself. It is broader than the instant of drawing the United States; it still contains no “Ronaldo.”\n\nPlaintiff’s Ronaldo evidence comes from a different artifact: the APP/reporter exchange, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange. Those sources are public, official, and topical, but they are still titled as remarks prior to the draw and marked by reporter-exchange features: joined in progress, photos, informal questions, inaudibles, and an incomplete-audio caveat. Plaintiff’s headings show that the exchange discussed the World Cup Draw; they do not establish that Kalshi’s market time period had already begun.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not help plaintiff bridge that gap. They require words during the specified time period and recognize that event scope, official presentation, broadcasts, recordings, and source hierarchy matter. The listed exclusions are not a license to count every public same-venue interaction unless expressly barred. If that were the rule, “during” would do almost no work.\n\nSo the final question is still burden, not semantics. Plaintiff had to prove that this market covered the prior reporter availability, not merely that the remarks were near, public, and about the same event. The formal-program comparator shows a coherent covered event without “Ronaldo.” The prior reporter exchange shows “Ronaldo” outside that established program. Without market-specific proof that Kalshi included that prior exchange, the No resolution remains the better reading.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case ends where it began: not with word mechanics, but with event scope.\n\nThe word mechanics are satisfied. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, identifies the Ronaldo strike and the market title: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” The packet transcript, ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, and the primary APP extract, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf, show Trump saying “Ronaldo” as a standalone word, more than once. The defense has not seriously disputed that.\n\nThe defense’s whole case is a proposed boundary: only the formal program counts, and the reporter exchange does not. But that boundary is not in the market title, not in the case-packet market page, and not in the mention terms. The title says “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” not “during the formal Rev transcript,” not “after Infantino says now we do the draw,” and not “excluding public pre-program venue remarks.”\n\nThe admitted record shows why the broader reading is more likely. The APP and packet transcripts are not private, backstage, rehearsal, sound-check, or unofficial materials. They are public remarks at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA President Infantino present, about the World Cup Draw, the host countries, ticket sales, teams, the audience, and the event setting. The APP extract preserves headings repeatedly tying the exchange to the “2026 World Cup Draw Event.” That is direct event context, not mere remote subject matter.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, help plaintiff because they show the Exchange knows how to exclude categories. It excludes behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Plaintiff’s transcript is none of those. The terms also allow event/context time periods. They do not impose a default formal-stage-only cutoff.\n\nDefendant’s best evidence, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, proves only that the formal-program comparator lacks Ronaldo. Plaintiff accepts that. But absence from one formal-program artifact is not exclusion from the market period. The Rev exhibit does not define Kalshi’s rule, does not identify the market’s start time, and does not say the public reporter exchange was outside the covered event. It actually confirms that even the formal “FIFA World Cup Drawing” program includes ceremony and remarks before the draw mechanics begin, so the event was never limited to the instant of drawing balls.\n\nThe defense asks plaintiff to produce an express inclusion clause for the reporter exchange. That reverses the practical issue. Kalshi resolved No. To sustain that No, the record should show a clear reason to throw out public, official, event-linked remarks in which the strike was spoken. The record does not show that. It shows a title broad enough to include them, terms that do not exclude them, and source evidence tying them to the event.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff does not need to prove every transcript says Ronaldo. Plaintiff needs to prove it is more likely than not that Trump said Ronaldo within the market’s event context. He did. The challenged No rests on an unstated formal-only limitation. The strike should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the closing record is simple in one respect and decisive in another. Trump said “Ronaldo” in the reporter-exchange transcript. Defendant has never needed to deny that. The question is whether plaintiff proved that this reporter exchange was inside the Kalshi market’s covered time period: “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” On that point, the record remains short of a preponderance.\n\nStart with the market evidence. The market page, ev_2c7c2c8a2d76_market-page, gives the public title, the contract family, the Ronaldo strike, and the challenged No resolution. It does not state that pre-program reporter availability, red-carpet questioning, or all same-venue event-linked remarks counted. Plaintiff’s closing repeatedly says there is no express exclusion. But lack of exclusion is not proof of inclusion. The settlement question is not “was the exchange related to the draw?” It is whether the word was said during the market’s specified event period.\n\nThe APP extract and packet transcript, ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf and ev_9cd6fa5297f3_pre-event-reporter-exchange, prove several things for plaintiff: the exchange was public, official enough to be transcribed, at the Kennedy Center, with Infantino present, and about the World Cup and draw setting. Those facts give the exchange context. They do not establish the market boundary. The same source title still says the remarks were in an exchange with reporters “Prior to” the FIFA World Cup Draw. The transcript was joined in progress, includes informal press movement and photo posing, and preserves inaudible/incomplete-audio caveats. That is a different source artifact from the formal program.\n\nThe terms, ev_a373371a8c9c_presmention-terms, do not shift the burden to defendant to find a magic exclusion. They require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They recognize event-based periods, source-agency decisions, official presentations, broadcasts, official recordings, and excluded unofficial or non-event material. The categories plaintiff emphasizes are not an all-purpose rule that everything public and topical counts. “During” still has to mean within the event period, not merely near the event.\n\nDefendant’s formal-program comparator, ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111, is important for exactly that reason. It is titled “FIFA World Cup Drawing,” includes ceremony, remarks, the peace-prize segment, Trump’s formal answer as draw assistant, and the draw process. So defendant is not arguing for a seconds-only draw-mechanics rule. The formal program can be broader than the ball draw. But in that broader formal-program evidence, “Ronaldo” is absent. The Ronaldo evidence comes from the separate reporter exchange described as prior to the draw.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the reporter exchange was event-linked. I accept that. But event-linked is not the same as within the market’s covered time period. The record contains no market-specific source page, no official market rule, and no broadcast or presentation evidence showing that the 11:13 a.m. reporter availability was part of the covered “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period. Without that link, plaintiff is asking the council to replace the market boundary with a general sense of event atmosphere.\n\nThe proposition asks the council to overturn a No resolution. The evidence proves a prior reporter exchange with Ronaldo, and a formal World Cup Drawing program without Ronaldo. It does not prove that Kalshi’s market required the prior exchange to count. On this record, the No resolution is the better-supported outcome.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and disputed strike\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Case-packet reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary APP transcript extract\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Mention-market terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Formal transcript source note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Formal-program transcript comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Mention-market terms on event scope\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Formal draw archive/source distinction\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 APP source title and provenance caveats\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 Formal-program comparator\nSource: Rev\nURL: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nPage title: FIFA World Cup Drawing\nPage description: Donald Trump attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing and FIFA Peace Prize ceremony. Read the transcript here.\nPublication date shown: December 8, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Web open and local HTTP fetch during defendant merits investigation, 2026-06-29T20:00:30Z.\n\nFocused formal-program transcript extract:\n\nGianni Infantino (00:16): Thank you. Thank you, Mr. President. Mr. President, this is your prize. This is your peace prize. There is also a beautiful medal for you that you can wear everywhere you want to go.\n\nDonald Trump (00:32): I'm going to wear it right now.\n\nGianni Infantino (00:33): Okay. Let me hold. Fantastic. Excellent. And you will receive also, of course, a certificate which reads out, and I would read it out with your permission what are the reasons for you receiving this FIFA Peace Prize Football Unites the world. So the FIFA Peace Prize is presented annually on behalf of the billions of football loving people from around the world to a distinguished individual who exemplifies an unwavering commitment to advancing peace and unity throughout the world, through their notable leadership and action. And therefore, FIFA, the Federation Anti-National, the Football Association, awards the 2025 FIFA Peace Prize. Football unites the world to Donald J. Trump, President of the United States of America, in recognition of his exceptional and extraordinary actions to promote peace and unity around the world. (01:42) Friday, December 5th, 2025. This is the certificate. It's yours. Before giving you the floor, Mr. President, if I may say two words...\n\nDonald Trump (03:55): Thank you. Well, thank you very much. This is truly one of the great honors of my life. And beyond awards, Gianni and I were discussing this, we saved millions and millions of lives. The Congo, as an example, over 10 million people killed and it was heading for another 10 million very quickly. And the fact that we could do that. India, Pakistan, so many different wars that were able to end. In some cases, a little bit before they started, just right before they started. It was going to be late, but we got them done. And it's such an honor to be with Gianni. I've known Gianni for so long. He's done such an incredible job. (04:36) And I have to tell you, you've set new records on ticket sales and not to bring that up because we don't want to bring a thing like that up right now, but it's an awfully nice tribute to you and to the game of football, or as we call it soccer, but football. And that is an amazing thing. The numbers are beyond any numbers that anybody, even beyond what Gianni thought was possible. I want to thank, by the way, my family, my great first lady, Melania, you're right here and thank you very much. And I think you're going to have an event, the likes of which maybe the world has never seen based on the enthusiasm that I've seen. I have never seen anything like it. (05:23) We've had a tremendous working relationship with Canada. We have our prime minister of Canada there and we have our president of Mexico and we've worked closely with those two countries. And the coordination and friendship and relationship has been outstanding. And I want to thank you both very much and your country very much. But most importantly, I just want to thank everybody. The world is a safer place now. The United States one year ago was not doing too well. And now I have to say we're the hottest country anywhere in the world and we're going to keep it that way. Thank you all. Thank you. Have a great time. And Gianni, a tremendous honor. Thank you.\n\nGianni Infantino (16:04): Behind, yes. [foreign language 00:15:44] Mexico, Claudia Sheinbaum. [foreign language 00:15:55]. And now the 45th and 47th President of the United States, Mr. Donald J. Trump. Mr. President, his way this way or his way, you can do what you want. This is your place. So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official ball for the World Cup. And we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant.\n\nGianni Infantino (18:29): Mr. President Trump, next summer is historic for the United States in more than one way. What does it mean to you that the FIFA World Cup is actually taking place in the United States 250th birthday? Special?\n\nDonald Trump (18:44): Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pelé, play on a team called the Cosmos. Pelé, who is fantastic, as you know, I assume one of the greats.\n\nGianni Infantino (19:03): Oh, yes. Pelé. Let's applaud Pelé, please. One of the greatest.\n\nDonald Trump (19:04): And he scored three goals out there. I said, \"That man can play.\" I was pretty young at that point. And who knew this was going to happen? But when you look at what has happened to football in the United States, again, soccer in the United States, we seem to never call it that because we have a little bit of a conflict with another thing that's called football. But when you think about it, shouldn't it really be called? I mean, this is football. There's no question about it. We have to come up with another name for the NFL stuff. It really doesn't make sense when you think about it. It's really football. But who would've thought it would've come to a level where you've set your all time season ticket ratings? Nobody's ever sold as many tickets and you're still a long way from that ball being kicked down the field. So I just want to congratulate you. What an incredible leap this has been, and congratulations to FIFA.\n\nGianni Infantino (20:05): Thank you. Thank you, President. Big round of applause. And the best is still to come, of course. So let's start with the draw. I will just show you how it works...\n\nGianni Infantino (22:01): President Trump, up to you. Don't forget to mingle. To mix.\n\nDonald Trump (22:05): I think I know what this is going to be now.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:07): Everything.\n\nDonald Trump (22:09): But let's see.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:10): Are you sure? Are you sure this is the ball? You can still change it if you want.\n\nDonald Trump (22:15): Does he know something that I don't know? Let's give it a shot.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:19): Let's give it a shot. Let's give it a shot. I agree. Okay.\n\nDonald Trump (22:27): This is shocking.\n\nGianni Infantino (22:29): United States of America. Excellent. Group D1. Can I ask all the three of you to lift like this on your chest, in front of your chest like this? Yeah. The name of the country, we will give a nice photo...\n\nDonald Trump (23:19): Come. Come.\n\nGianni Infantino (23:23): Come, come. Thank you very much.\n\nDonald Trump (23:32): Thank you everybody.\n\nLocal text-search note: the fetched Rev page text contained zero case-insensitive matches for \"ronaldo\". This note records the extraction/search method; the transcript extract above is the preserved source content.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 APP prior reporter exchange source\nSource: The American Presidency Project, University of California Santa Barbara\nURL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nPage title: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDate shown on page: December 05, 2025\nRetrieval/capture: Browser open during plaintiff merits investigation, 2026-06-29T19:56:00Z. This is a focused text extract of relevant page text and headings.\n\nRelevant page text:\n\n# Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\n\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\n\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\n\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\n\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\n\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\n\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\n\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\n\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\n\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[i naudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\n\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\n\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\n\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\n\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\n\n2026 World Cup\n\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\n\nNote preserved from case-packet transcript for provenance/limitations: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Event-scope terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] American Presidency Project transcript extract: pre-draw reporter exchange (ev_c7c5425b23cf_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-c7c5425b23cf)\nSource: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\nSHA-256: `c7c5425b23cf65ee377a9e441fd03caee1a5163b01726ac5f2d1067bfb11cf6b`\nBytes: 6110\nRelevance: Primary public transcript source for the reporter exchange already in the case packet; corroborates venue/event framing and the material Ronaldo passages.\n\n[defendant arguments] Rev transcript extract: formal FIFA World Cup Drawing program (ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111)\nSource: https://www.rev.com/transcripts/fifa-world-cup-drawing\nSHA-256: `177c6733211159ba2d1193689bf2f513445144f83bf732788a5ef72753122980`\nBytes: 7153\nRelevance: Provides a formal-program transcript comparator for the FIFA World Cup Drawing, distinct from the pre-event reporter exchange. The captured page text was searched locally for 'Ronaldo' with zero matches; the focused extract includes the formal Trump remarks and draw-assistant segment.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\nSearched exact Ronaldo/World Cup Draw phrases and source-specific repositories. Browser retrieved the American Presidency Project primary transcript page and plaintiff submitted a focused extract as PX-3. A direct curl attempt to that page timed out with zero bytes, so browser text capture was used. The Kalshi URL rendered a same-event page but with a different selected strike, so plaintiff did not submit it to avoid confusing the Ronaldo record. White House video page title/date were checked but the page text did not contain the Ronaldo passage. Roll Call/Factba.se formal transcript was checked as an adverse source; browser find found no Ronaldo/Cristiano match, and the existing packet note already preserves the formal-transcript gap.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and formal-transcript ledger\nReviewed the full visible evidence list and read plaintiff's new APP transcript extract. Searched/opened formal-program sources including Rev, Roll Call/Factba.se, and White House video leads. Rev was retrievable without credentials; local Python stdlib fetch returned HTTP 200, 132,861 HTML bytes, and 56,928 chars of extracted page text. Case-insensitive search of the fetched Rev text found zero 'ronaldo' matches. Defendant submitted a focused Rev formal-program extract as ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. Limits: Rev is a secondary transcript rather than Kalshi's market source; I did not obtain market-specific Kalshi rule text expanding the time period to pre-program reporter exchanges, nor an official livestream source showing the reporter exchange was part of the formal presentation.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal review of defendant Rev transcript\nPlaintiff read the full 7,153-byte defendant Rev extract. It lacks Ronaldo, but it does not define Kalshi market scope. The extract also shows the formal 'FIFA World Cup Drawing' program included peace-prize and other remarks before Infantino announced they were now going to do the draw, undercutting a literal draw-mechanics-only boundary.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defendant reviewed the current record with get_case and list_evidence. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new submitted evidence; the visible evidence list remained the packet files, plaintiff APP extract, and defendant Rev formal-program extract. Defendant also checked metadata for ev_177c67332111_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-177c67332111. No new source search was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal point was interpretive: whether the formal program's breadth implies inclusion of the separate prior reporter exchange.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T21:02:47.560758432Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":870013,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782766097562}]}
